04643nam a22006735i 9780824854799DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20152015hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248547997 a10.1515/97808248547992doi  a(DE-B1597)484383  a(OCoLC)905636927  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aREL0240002bisacsh04a299.5/9222231 aHoskins, Janet Alison, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Divine Eye and the Diaspora :bVietnamese Syncretism Becomes Transpacific Caodaism /cJanet Alison Hoskins. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (308 p.) :b8 color and 17 black & white illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tChronology -- tIntroduction: “Outrageous Syncretism”? -- tChapter 1. Conversations with Divinities -- tChapter 2. A Spirit Medium as Nationalist Leader -- tChapter 3. The Spiritual Sons of Victor Hugo -- tChapter 4. The Fall of Saigon and the Rise of the Diaspora -- tChapter 5. A “Caodaist in Black” Returns to Live in Vietnam -- tChapter 6. The Divine Eye on the Internet -- tChapter 7. A Religion in Diaspora, A Religion of Diaspora -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tABOUT THE AUTHOR0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat is the relationship between syncretism and diaspora? Caodaism is a large but almost unknown new religion that provides answers to this question. Born in Vietnam during the struggles of decolonization, shattered and spatially dispersed by cold war conflicts, it is now reshaping the goals of its four million followers. Colorful and strikingly eclectic, its “outrageous syncretism” incorporates Chinese, Buddhist, and Western religions as well as world figures like Victor Hugo, Jeanne d’Arc, Vladimir Lenin, and (in the USA) Joseph Smith, the founder of Mormonism. The book looks at the connections between “the age of revelations” (1925-1934) in French Indochina and the “age of diaspora” (1975-present) when many Caodai leaders and followers went into exile. Structured in paired biographies to trace relations between masters and disciples, now separated by oceans, it focuses on five members of the founding generation and their followers or descendants in California, showing the continuing obligation to honor those who forged the initial vision to “bring the gods of the East and West together.” Diasporic congregations in California have interacted with New Age ideas and stereotypes of a “Walt Disney fantasia of the East,” at the same time that temples in Vietnam have re-opened their doors after decades of severe restrictions.Caodaism forces us to reconsider how anthropologists study religious mixtures in postcolonial settings. Its dynamics challenge the unconscious Eurocentrism of our notions of how religions are bounded and conceptualized.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCaodaism. 0aSyncretism (Religion)zVietnam. 7aRELIGION / Eastern.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2014-2016z978311056413640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082485479940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824854799423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824854799.jpg  a978-3-11-056413-6  UHP eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-070098-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK